>h2 Help System
>tree open Help System
`help` reads `//help:` lines directly from `/bin/*.cc` and `/home/bin/*.cc`.

That means command source is also command documentation.

Use:
  help
  help <command>

>button help | shell:help
>button help ls | shell:help ls
>endtree

>h2 Shell Built-Ins
>tree open Shell Built-Ins
Built-ins verified in `kernel/shell.c`:
- `cupid`
- `exec`
- `notepad`
- `terminal`
- `ps`
- `cc`
- `reset`
- `cupidc`
- `ccc`
- `as`
- `cupidasm`
- `jobs`
>endtree

>h2 Execution Shortcuts
>tree open Execution Shortcuts
The shell also treats extensions specially:
- `file.cup`  -> `cupid file.cup`
- `file.cc`   -> `cupidc file.cc`
- `file.asm`  -> `as file.asm`
- `./path`    -> execute by extension or binary loader

Disassembly shortcuts:
- `cc -d file.cc`
- `exec -d file`
>endtree

>h2 Auto-Discovery Order
>tree Auto-Discovery Order
Command lookup order after built-ins:
1) `/bin/<cmd>`
2) `/bin/<cmd>.cc`
3) `/home/bin/<cmd>`
4) `/home/bin/<cmd>.cc`

This is the TempleOS-style source-first workflow for shipped and user programs.
>button ls /bin | shell:ls /bin
>button ls /home/bin | shell:ls /home/bin
>endtree

>h2 File and Directory Commands
>tree open File and Directory Commands
Source-backed command set from shipped `/bin/*.cc`:
- `ls [path]`
- `pwd`
- `cd [path]`
- `cat <file>`
- `cp <source> <dest>`
- `mv <source> <dest>`
- `rm <file...>`
- `mkdir <dir...>`
- `rmdir <dir...>`
- `touch <file...>`
- `find [path] [name]`
- `grep <pattern> <path> [path] ...`
- `mount`
- `ed [file]`

>button ls /docs | shell:ls /docs
>button pwd | shell:pwd
>button mount | shell:mount
>button find /docs CTXT | shell:find /docs CTXT
>button grep DolDoc /docs | shell:grep DolDoc /docs
>endtree

